          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "And it fell on a day",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] From its use elsewhere the Hebrew noun, as here, with the article signifies ‘on that day’, ‘at that time’, and indicates a closer connexion with the preceding narrative than would be gathered from the A.V. But see below, verses 11 and 18.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Elisha passed to Shunem",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] In ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joshua 19:18",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", Shunem is among the places allotted to the tribe of Issachar. It is also mentioned as the place where the Philistines encamped before the battle of Gilboa (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Samuel 28:4",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). It has been identified with ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Solam",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", a village situate on the little Hermon about 3 miles north of Jezreel. When Elisha was travelling either from Samaria or Jezreel to Carmel, Shunem lay on his road. The place is mentioned as being the home of Abishag (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 1:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") and from that is derived the Jewish tradition which makes the Shunammite woman of the present narrative to have been the sister of Abishag.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "a great woman",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] The adjective is used to signify ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "wealthy",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Samuel 25:2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", of Nabal, and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Samuel 19:32",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " of Barzillai, who is described as ‘a very great man’. As the Shunammite woman had a husband still alive, it would be more natural to speak of him as ‘great’ in the sense of ‘rich’, and perhaps here the meaning is rather ‘influential’. She was clearly a person of independent character, and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "one who",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " could act when the occasion demanded it.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "she constrained him to eat bread",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] The journeys of Elisha to and fro had somehow become known to her and she offered him hospitality. This was the usual way in the East, where houses for public entertainment were uncommon.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "as oft as he passed by",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] Apparently the allusion is to such rounds as the chief of the prophetic colleges would make to the different centres at which they were gathered. That Elisha’s visits were frequent is clear from the next verse.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verses 8-37.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - 2. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "The promise of a child to the Shunammite woman",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "and the restoration of the child to life",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 8.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "And it fall on a day, that.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " The expression seems to be archaic. It occurs only here and in the opening chapters of the Book of Job (Job 1:6, 13; 2:1). The most literal rendering would be, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "and the day came when",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Elisha passed to Shunem. Shunem was a village of Galilee, situated in the territory assigned to Issachar (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joshua 19:18",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). It is reasonably identified with the modern ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "Solam",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", at the south-eastern foot of the Gebel Duhy, or \"Little Hermon,\" a \"flourishing village encompassed by gardens\" (Porter), and \"in the midst of the finest corn-fields in the world\" (Grove), on the edge of the Plain of Esdraelon. Elisha, in his progression to different parts of the northern kingdom, happened to come on one occasion to Shunem. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Where was a great woman.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " Houbigant strangely translates, \"a tan woman,\" maintaining that a woman would not be called \"great\" in the sense of \"wealthy\" during her husband's lifetime; but no other commentator has accepted his view. The meaning seems to be that she was a woman of substance, one well-to-do, perhaps one that had brought her husband the bulk of his wealth. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "And she constrained him to eat bread",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "i.e.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " she invited him in as he passed her house, and would take no denial. Compare Lot's pressing hospitality, as related in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 19:1-3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "And so it was, that as oft as he passed by, he turned in thither to eat bread.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " Elisha, it appears, had frequent occasion to pass through Shunem on his way from Carmel to visit the cities of Galilee, or ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "versa",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". It became his habit, on these journeys, to eat his meals at the house of the rich Shunammite. Hence arose a kindly feeling on both sides and a close intimacy. 2 Kings 4:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The Shunammite and her Son. - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 4:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". When Elisha was going one day (lit., the day, i.e., at that time, then) to Shunem (Solam, at the south-western foot of the Lesser Hermon; see at ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 1:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), a wealthy woman (גּדולה as in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Samuel 25:2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", etc.) constrained him to eat at her house; whereupon, as often as he passed by that place in his subsequent journeys from Carmel to Jezreel and back, he was accustomed to call upon her (סוּר as in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 19:2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ").",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
]